    <head>
        <title>Equally Likely Outcomes (2 of 2)</title>
        <objref idref="find_probability_for_equally_likely_outcomes"/>
    </head>
    <body>
      
        <p>Here is a more interesting example:</p>
        <example>

            <p>A certain college recently announced
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095725-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095723-0500" content="two"?>
                job openings in its admissions office. From all the applicants, a search committee
                identified
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095732-0500"?>5<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095730-0500" content="five"?>
                candidates<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095059-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095056-0500" content="---t"?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095736-0500" content="wo"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095740-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?>
                men and
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095742-0500" content="three"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095744-0500"?>3<?oxy_insert_end?>
                women<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095045-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095042-0500" content="---"?>who
                seemed equally qualified. Priding itself on a long history as an equal opportunity
                employer, the college would like to continue that tradition and make the
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095755-0500" content="two"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095756-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?>
                appointments at random. The college's legal department, though, has cautioned the
                personnel office that
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T103434-0500"?>doing
                so<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T103431-0500" content="that"?>
                may not be a good idea. If the
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095801-0500" content="two"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095803-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?>
                chosen happen to be of the same gender, the selection process will seem to be
                discriminatory, and the college may become embroiled in expensive litigation. What
                is the probability that the random selection will
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095238-0500"?>result in both
                chosen candidates having the same gender, and will thus <?oxy_insert_end?>appear to
                be discriminatory? We'll denote this event by D (for discriminatory).</p>
            <p>Let's identify the
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100039-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100037-0500" content="two"?>
                men and
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100043-0500"?>3<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100041-0500" content="three"?>
                women as M1, M2, F1,
                F2<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095342-0500" content=","?> and
                F3. </p>
            <p>Our random experiment is choosing
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100051-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100050-0500" content="two"?>
                out of these
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100054-0500"?>5<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100053-0500" content="five"?>
                candidates at random, and the sample space of all possible outcomes of this random
                experiment is therefore:</p>
            <p> S = { (M1,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095550-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>M2), (M1,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095552-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F1), (M1,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095553-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F2), (M1,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095555-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F3), (M2,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095556-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F1), (M2,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095558-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F2), (M2,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095600-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F3), (F1,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095602-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F2), (F1,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095604-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F3), (F2,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095606-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>F3) }. </p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image008.gif" alt="All of the possible outcomes in
the sample space."/>
            <p>Note that
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095504-0500"?>because
                <?oxy_insert_end?>the order in which the selection is made does not
                matter,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095512-0500"?> and
                because 2 candidates are being chosen and they are listed in S as pairs,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095534-0500" content="and so "?>once
                we've included (M1,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095541-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>M2) in S, we should not also include (M2,<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T095619-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>M1). Both represent the same outcome: M1 and M2 are the two that
                were chosen to get the jobs.</p>
            <p>Thus S consists of 10 outcomes, all equally likely, since the selection of any
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100819-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100818-0500" content="two"?>
                out of the
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100824-0500"?>5<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100822-0500" content="five"?>
                has been done at random. </p>
            <p>We are interested in event
                D<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100843-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T100839-0500" content=" - "?>that
                the selection process will appear to be discriminatory, or in other words that the
                two chosen will be of the same gender. Event D consists of 4 of the 10 possible
                outcomes:</p>
            <p> D = { (M1,M2), (F1,F2), (F1,F3), (F2,F3) }</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image009.gif" alt="All of the 10 possible outcomes,
with the 4 outcomes in D highlighted. "/>
            <p>The probability that the selection will appear to be discriminatory is therefore:</p>


