        <section>
            <title>Comment</title>
            <body>
                <p>It should be noted that in this example it was still manageable to list all the
                    possible outcomes, and then
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101328-0500"?>count<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101330-0500" content="do the counting of"?>
                    the number of outcomes that are in event D. If we were to change the example
                    slightly, and needed to choose 2 candidates out
                    of<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101352-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    say, 10 (instead of 5), the number of possible outcomes would grow substantially
                    (from 10 to 45) and listing all of those outcomes would be quite
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101513-0500"?>time-consuming
                    and
                    <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101608-0500" comment="OK to change tiring (just causing fatigue) to tiresome (cuasing fatigue and boredom)?"?>tir<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101421-0500"?>esome<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101419-0500" content="ing"?><?oxy_comment_end?>.
                    Later in the probability section we will learn some simple counting
                    methods<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101616-0500" content=", which"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T101621-0500"?>
                    that<?oxy_insert_end?> will allow us to figure out the number of possible
                    outcomes without actually listing them.</p>
            </body>
        </section>
